---
// About / mission. This is the page that carries the project's voice — why it
// exists, who "we" is, and why the scope is deliberately small. Everything here
// must stay true today (same rule as the accessibility statement): no roadmap
// claims written in the present tense.
// On-demand so a visitor's saved accessibility settings apply while they read it.
export const prerender = false;

import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About"
  description="Why Access Atlas exists, who builds it, and why it starts in Buffalo and Erie County rather than everywhere."
>
  <h1>About Access Atlas</h1>

  <p class="lead">
    Access Atlas is a directory of accessible places and disabled-led providers in
    Buffalo and Erie County, built by disabled people. It exists because the
    accessibility information we could already find was not written by anyone who
    had to use it.
  </p>

  {/*
    TODO (Zach) — the opening scene. This is the one paragraph nobody else can
    write: a specific local instance of the failure, in the first person. The
    listing that said accessible and meant a step at the door; the clinic whose
    accessible entrance was locked after five; whatever the real one is. Roughly
    80 words, concrete, one place, one day. The rest of this page is built to
    land after it — it currently reads as an argument without its evidence.
  */}

  <h2>What goes wrong</h2>
  <p>
    Accessibility information fails in a predictable way. It is written by the
    people who own the building rather than the people who have to get into it,
    so it records intent instead of reality — a ramp that exists but is chained
    shut, a “step-free entrance” around the back through the kitchen. Then it gets
    flattened into a single star rating, which is the second failure: one number
    cannot tell a wheelchair user and a Deaf visitor and someone with light
    sensitivity what any of them needs to know. The information is not
    insufficient. It is written from the wrong side of the door.
  </p>

  <h2>Who “we” is</h2>
  <p>
    Access Atlas is disabled-led. The people deciding what counts as an
    accessibility fact here are people who get stopped by the lack of one. That is
    not a credential we are claiming for marketing purposes — it is the reason the
    labels on this site are shaped the way they are. Every trust label exists
    because someone who needed the information got burned by its absence, and
    wanted to know how much to trust it before making the trip.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Buffalo and Erie County</h2>
  <p>
    A national directory of unverified listings would be easy to build and worth
    nothing. Every accessibility claim here has to be confirmed in person, by
    someone who was actually there, which means coverage can only grow at the speed
    people can walk and roll through it. So we started in one place, close to home,
    where we can check.
  </p>
  <p>
    This means the directory is thin. We would rather it be thin and true. A
    listing that is missing costs you a search somewhere else; a listing that is
    wrong costs you a trip, and sometimes a good deal more than that.
  </p>

  <h2>What we will not do</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      We will never reduce accessibility to one star rating. Each fact stands on
      its own, because each person needs different ones.
    </li>
    <li>
      We will never require proof of disability. Owners self-attest; visitors
      contribute pseudonymously. There is no medical gatekeeping here, ever.
    </li>
    <li>
      We will never call self-reported information “verified”. Those are different
      labels and they stay different, even when the directory looks emptier for it.
    </li>
    <li>
      We will never sell your data or load third-party trackers to watch you read.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to check us</h2>
  <p>
    Everything above is checkable, which is the point. Our
    <a href="/about/privacy/">trust labels</a> are defined in public and say exactly
    what each one is worth. Our <a href="/about/accessibility/">accessibility
    statement</a> describes what the site does today, links the evidence for the
    one hard number it cites, and admits what our automated testing misses. The
    code is open.
  </p>

  <div class="disclaimer">
    <p>
      If you know a place in Buffalo or Erie County that belongs here — or one we
      have listed wrong — <a href="/contribute/submit/">tell us</a>. A single
      credible report that somewhere is not accessible freezes the claim while we
      re-check it. We would rather be corrected than trusted.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
